[4] Virginia
Date: Thu 2 Oct 2014
Source: The News & Advance, Richmond Times Dispatch report [edited]
http://www.newsadvance.com/news/state/va-department-of-health-probes-link-between-enterovirus-and-paralysis/article_1cf4706d-7d1f-5e5c-af4d-b0935ccce93d.html


The Virginia Department of Health has received one report of a child developing acute neurological illness similar to the limb weakness reported in a cluster of 9 [now 10] Colorado children sickened by a severe respiratory illness.

Health officials continue to investigate a link between paralysis or weakness and infection with enterovirus D68, which is afflicting children across the country.

The Virginia child is from the northern health region, said Dr. Laurie Forlano, Virginia state epidemiologist.

"We've had one report of what seems like some compatible illness. That information has been passed on to the [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]."

The CDC on [26 Sep 2014] sent out an advisory to health care providers to be alert for acute paralysis in children infected with enterovirus D68 after health care providers in Colorado reported the cluster of cases.

So far, the only CDC lab-confirmed enterovirus D68 cases in Virginia are from the central health region.

Nationally, enterovirus D68 infections have been confirmed in 42 states and the District of Columbia.

[Byline: Tammie Smith]

