******
[5] Alabama, RFI
Date: Wed 1 Oct 2014
Source: Dothan Eagle [edited]
http://www.dothaneagle.com/enterprise_ledger/news/state-confirms-new-case-of-enterovirus-amid-reports-of-paralysis/article_b98c059e-49b4-11e4-b47e-0017a43b2370.html


Alabama health officials on Tuesday [30 Sep 2014] confirmed a 5th case of the enterovirus D68 respiratory illness and said they are looking into "an unknown neurological illness" seen in a few children across the country.

Dr. Mary McIntyre, state epidemiologist with the Alabama Department of Public Health, said officials have not confirmed the neurological symptoms, and that the state has only received information on one child.

The neurological symptoms include muscle weakness and paralysis, according to news reports. The department is asking doctors to be on the lookout for the symptoms.

McIntyre said that as of Tuesday, 40 people had been evaluated for the virus, and 9 patients in hospitals had been tested. Of those 9, 5 have tested positive for enterovirus D68. This includes the 4 cases confirmed last month [September 2014], McIntyre said.

But that doesn't mean there are only 5 cases of the virus in the state. The state is only testing a few of the most severe cases that have met key criteria, because the state lab does not have the capability to test for each suspected case. She encouraged doctors to call 1-800-338-8374 prior to sending specimens to the state for testing.

Dr. John McLendon, a pediatrician with Enterprise Pediatrics, said his practice likely saw several cases of the virus in asthmatic patients between mid-August [2014] and mid-September [2014], when a larger-than-usual number of children came in with respiratory problems.

"Children came in with really bad asthma flares," McLendon said. "We don't have a good way to test for enterovirus, but there was definitely something going on and that makes the most sense."

While the virus does not have a cure, it can be treated with rest and fluids and medication that relieves symptoms. Asthma patients should take their controller medications to prevent attacks, he said.

McLendon said the number of patients coming in with severe respiratory problems seems to have slowed in recent weeks, however.

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said symptoms of the illness include fever, runny nose, sneezing, cough and body and muscle aches. Severe symptoms may include wheezing and difficulty breathing.

The virus can be found in an infected person's saliva, mucus or sputum, according to the CDC website. It spreads from person to person when an infected person coughs, sneezes or touches surfaces.

Prevention is still the best defense, said McIntyre. To keep from getting sick, residents are advised to wash hands for at least 20 seconds with soap and warm water, stay home when sick and sanitize frequently used objects and appliances, such as doorknobs.

[Byline: Jennifer Calhoun]

